BT /F1 9 Tf 42 550 Td (confidence cases are escalated to the strong model. Without calibration, fallback decisions) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 539 Td (would be less stable and could either waste money or hurt answer quality.) Tj ET
BT /F2 11 Tf 42 518 Td (4. WHY IS THE FALLBACK THRESHOLD `0.55`, AND HOW WOULD YOU TUNE IT IN PRODUCTION?) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 504 Td (`0.55` is a practical MVP starting point that gives the router some caution without sending) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 493 Td (too many prompts to the expensive tier. In production, I would tune it using offline) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 482 Td (evaluation plus real traffic analysis by measuring the tradeoff between cost, latency, and) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 471 Td (routing mistakes. The right threshold depends on business tolerance for bad answers versus API) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 460 Td (spend.) Tj ET
BT /F2 11 Tf 42 439 Td (5. HOW DO YOU BALANCE LATENCY, QUALITY, AND COST ACROSS WEAK, MODERATE, AND STRONG MODELS?) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 425 Td (The main idea is to reserve expensive capacity for prompts that actually need it. Weak prompts) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 414 Td (go to the cheapest local model, moderate prompts go to a stronger local model, and strong or) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 403 Td (uncertain prompts go to the cloud model. That gives low latency and near-zero cost for simpler) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 392 Td (work while protecting quality on complex requests.) Tj ET
BT /F2 11 Tf 42 371 Td (6. WHY USE OLLAMA FOR LOCAL MODELS AND OPENAI/GEMINI FOR THE STRONG TIER?) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 357 Td (Ollama is a good fit for local inference because it is simple to run, supports multiple local) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 346 Td (models, and keeps cheap requests off paid APIs. OpenAI and Gemini are good strong-tier options) Tj ET
BT /F1 9 Tf 42 335 Td (because they provide high-quality frontier models through stable APIs. This hybrid design) Tj ET
